README.md
     1в†’# Command-line tool
     3в†’The `mdbook` command-line tool is used to create and build books.
     4в†’After you have [installed](../guide/installation.md) `mdbook`, you can run the `mdbook help` command in your terminal to view the available commands.
     5в†’
     6в†’This following sections provide in-depth information on the different commands available.
     7в†’
     8в†’* [`mdbook init <directory>`](init.md) --- Creates a new book with minimal boilerplate to start with.
     9в†’* [`mdbook build`](build.md) --- Renders the book.
    10в†’* [`mdbook watch`](watch.md) --- Rebuilds the book any time a source file changes.
    11в†’* [`mdbook serve`](serve.md) --- Runs a web server to view the book, and rebuilds on changes.
    12в†’* [`mdbook test`](test.md) --- Tests Rust code samples.
    13в†’* [`mdbook clean`](clean.md) --- Deletes the rendered output.
    14в†’* [`mdbook completions`](completions.md) --- Support for shell auto-completion.

arg-watcher.md
     1в†’#### `--watcher`
     3в†’There are different backends used to determine when a file has changed.
     4в†’
     5в†’* `poll` (default) --- Checks for file modifications by scanning the filesystem every second.
     6в†’* `native` --- Uses the native operating system facilities to receive notifications when files change.
