completions.md
     1в†’# The completions command
     3в†’The completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4в†’This means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
     5в†’
     6в†’The completions first need to be installed for your shell:
     7в†’
     8в†’```bash
     9в†’# bash
    10в†’mdbook completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/mdbook
    11в†’# oh-my-zsh
    12в†’mdbook completions zsh > ~/.oh-my-zsh/completions/_mdbook
    13в†’autoload -U compinit && compinit
    14в†’```
    15в†’
    16в†’The command prints a completion script for the given shell.
    17в†’Run `mdbook completions --help` for a list of supported shells.
    18в†’
    19в†’Where to place the completions depend on which shell you are using and your operating system.
      в†’вЂ¦

init.md
     1в†’# The init command
     3в†’There is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4в†’this purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
     5в†’
     6в†’The `init` command is used like this:
     7в†’
     8в†’```bash
     9в†’mdbook init
    10в†’```
    11в†’
    12в†’When using the `init` command for the first time, a couple of files will be set
    13в†’up for you:
    14в†’```bash
    15в†’book-test/
    16в†’в”њв”Ђв”Ђ book
    17в†’в””в”Ђв”Ђ src
    18в†’    в”њв”Ђв”Ђ chapter_1.md
    19в†’    в””в”Ђв”Ђ SUMMARY.md
    20в†’```
    21в†’
