test.md
     1в†’# The test command
     3в†’When writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4в†’[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5в†’of code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6в†’them to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7в†’
     8в†’mdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9в†’the moment, only Rust tests are supported.
    10в†’
    11в†’#### Disable tests on a code block
    31в†’#### Specify a directory
    40в†’#### `--library-path`
    57в†’#### `--chapter`

watch.md
     1в†’# The watch command
     3в†’The `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4в†’file change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5в†’changed. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6в†’build automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7в†’deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8в†’
     9в†’#### Specify a directory
    18в†’#### `--open`
    23в†’#### `--dest-dir`
